&lt;h3 id=&#34;introduction&#34;&gt;Introduction&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;small&gt;
A novel task that directly synthesizes spoken descriptions for images bypassing any text or phoneme information is proposed. This task, which is referred to as image speaking is to realize the process of image-to-speech generation. To implement this new task, a framework named as show and speak (SAS) is proposed. This SAS model treats the image speaking as a sequence-to-sequence process, which takes a sequence of image local features as input and predicts a sequence of spectrogram of speech. The final speech audio can be obtained from the predicted spectrogram via WaveNet. Extensive experiments on the public benchmark database Flickr8k demonstrate that the proposed SAS is able to synthesize high-quality spoken descriptions for images, indicating that synthesizing spoken descriptions for images while bypassing text and phoneme is feasible. The proposed SAS provides a proof-of-concept and a baseline for the image speaking task.
